    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Peucedanum wrightii improperly include experiencing nausea, induce vomiting, cause diarrhea, induce nausea, and develop an allergic reaction. These adverse reactions may occur due to the plant's toxic compounds, such as falcarinol and bergapten, which can cause gastrointestinal irritation, stimulate the vomiting center in the brain, and trigger allergic responses. Prolonged or excessive consumption can lead to the accumulation of these toxic compounds in the body, exacerbating the adverse effects. Furthermore, improper preparation or dosing of Peucedanum wrightii can also increase the risk of side effects. Ingestion of large quantities or prolonged use without medical supervision may necessitate medical attention to prevent potential harm.",
    "uses": "Peucedanum wrightii, also known as Wright's carrot fern, is a plant that has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. The plant's leaves and roots are said to possess anti-inflammatory and antibacterial properties, which are believed to aid in treating fever, cough, and other respiratory issues. In folk medicine, the plant is also used to treat digestive problems, such as diarrhea and indigestion. Additionally, its extracts are thought to have antioxidant and anti-cancer properties, although more research is needed to confirm these claims. However, it is essential to consult with a healthcare professional before using any plant-based remedies for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Peucedanum wrightii is classified as a species of flowering plant in the carrot family, Apiaceae. It is a member of the genus Peucedanum, which includes various species of ferns and flowering plants native to the tropical and subtropical regions of Asia. Within the Apiaceae family, Peucedanum wrightii is further grouped into the subfamily Apioideae. This subfamily comprises a large number of species, many of which are used as food or medicine. The classification of Peucedanum wrightii highlights its relationship to other plants in the carrot family and its unique characteristics within that group.",
    "benefits": "Peucedanum wrightii, also known as Wright's umbrella-parsley, is a plant native to the Philippines. While there is limited information available, Peucedanum wrightii is believed to have potential health benefits due to its antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. The plant's extracts may help to reduce inflammation and protect against cell damage. Additionally, its compounds may have antimicrobial effects, which could aid in the prevention of infections. Further research is needed to confirm the full extent of Peucedanum wrightii's health benefits.",
    "parts": "Peucedanum wrightii is a plant species native to the Philippines, and like other members of the carrot family, it is utilized for its medicinal properties. The roots, leaves, and seeds of Peucedanum wrightii are used in traditional medicine to treat various ailments. The roots are believed to have antiseptic and anti-inflammatory properties, making them useful for treating skin conditions and wounds. The leaves and seeds are also used to treat digestive issues and fever. However, the effectiveness and safety of using Peucedanum wrightii for medicinal purposes require further research and verification.",
    "intro": "Peucedanum wrightii, also known as Wright's masterwort, is a species of flowering plant in the carrot family (Apiaceae). This plant has been traditionally used in folk medicine for its various health benefits, including its anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may help alleviate symptoms of fever, cough, and respiratory issues. The bioactive constituents of Peucedanum wrightii include coumarins, flavonoids, and sesquiterpenes, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In herbal medicine, Peucedanum wrightii is often prepared as a tea or infused in a decoction to treat various ailments, and it is also used to make a medicinal oil and tincture."
